<article>
    <h1>Us&#xAD;ing so&#xAD;cial me&#xAD;dia re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;si&#xAD;bly</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200921/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-21"><time>2020-09-21</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | MIND &amp; BODY</span>
        - <span role="byline">By JUSTIN CHUA</span>
    </section>

    <p>The preva­lence of so­cial me­dia has made it eas­ier than ever to be­come some­one else. Be­hind the lay­ers of photo fil­ters, auto-tuned voices, and phan­tom fol­low­ers, de­ter­min­ing an hon­est iden­tity can some­times be a chal­lenge.</p>
    <p>And with this semi-face­less­ness comes a lack of re­spon­si­bil­ity and ac­count­abil­ity, that in turn feed the flames of mal­ice. Ever so of­ten, you hear of the on­line abuse case that ca­su­ally spi­rals out of con­trol — ul­ti­mately re­duc­ing a poor soul to a mere statis­tic. That kid from a bro­ken fam­ily teased and taunted be­cause un­like the rest of the “nor­mal” kids in school, his jeans come tat­tered not by de­sign. Even high-pro­file pub­lic fig­ures like pro­fes­sional ath­letes are not spared, with many sub­jected to the viper­ous fin­gers of frus­trated fans fol­low­ing an un­sat­is­fac­tory re­sult.</p>
    <p>There is an un­de­ni­able re­spon­si­bil­ity we share as users of so­cial me­dia. Here are a few ways that can help mould us all into law-abid­ing on­line cit­i­zens.</p>
    <p>If you have noth­ing good to say…</p>
    <p>Say noth­ing at all. Bear in mind that the tar­get of your hos­til­ity has feel­ings too, just like you. What will you es­tab­lish if you do go ahead with the in­sults? If you are look­ing to let off steam, there are other more prac­ti­cal out­lets to do so.</p>
    <p>Block and report</p>
    <p>If you do come across vile ac­counts, do your part by rais­ing the is­sue with the pow­ers that be. This will usu­ally fol­low with a tem­po­rary or per­ma­nent ac­count ban, and even po­lice in­ter­ven­tion if nec­es­sary.</p>
    <p>Do not re­tal­i­ate</p>
    <p>“Troll” ac­counts ex­ist solely to in­sti­gate re­tal­i­a­tion. The peo­ple be­hind such move­ments dole out con­tro­ver­sial con­tent in the hopes of draw­ing out a neg­a­tive re­ac­tion. Avoid play­ing into their hands, but do not ig­nore this. Block­ing and re­port­ing as per the point above would be a good start.</p>

